text: As an adopted Ethiopian boy in America I am surrounded by American people But I kept my Ethiopian language and culture so close Now I am grown up and have my own apartment and unfortunately here in America your neighbor usually complains when you open laud music So I played Dishta Gina laud on the speaker dancing and singing at the same time So two white American neighbors showed up at my door I told them right away that I was sorry and that I will turn the volume down Their answer oh no we dont you to turn it down we just want to know the name of the song I invited them into my apartment and showed them the whole music video and they start dancing with me Just wanted to say THE POWER OF OUR ETHIOPIAN CULTURE
original: As an adopted Ethiopian boy in America, I am surrounded by American people. But I kept my Ethiopian language and culture so close. Now, I am grown up and have my own apartment and unfortunately here in America your neighbor usually complains when you open laud music. So, I played Dishta Gina laud on the speaker dancing and singing at the same time. So, two white American neighbors showed up at my door. I told them right away that I was sorry and that I will turn the volume down. Their answer, "oh no we don't you to turn it down, we just want to know the name of the song." I invited them into my apartment and showed them the whole music video, and they start dancing with me. Just wanted to say.... THE POWER OF OUR ETHIOPIAN CULTURE!

text: Let me break it down to you in French brother Cette chanson est devenue populaire grâce au grand message langue Ari sud de lÉthiopie et quelques paroles en amharique à la fin Il chante nous sommes tous les descendants dAdam et Eve Nous devons donc nous aimer en tant que frères et sœurs Nous sommes de la terre nous retournons a la terre Le salut ne peut pas venir de la prétention Je suis de cette race ou je suis de cette ethnie Notre acte sur la terre est notre garantie de salut Nous devons éviter le tribalisme et le racisme et nous aimer les uns les autres peu importe doù nous venons Dishtagina est la nouvelle année du peuple Ari Il dit que le passé soit révolu et reçois la nouvelle année avec un nouvel espoir et un nouvel amour
original:
Let me break it down to you in French brother. Cette chanson est devenue populaire grâce au grand message: (langue Ari, sud de l'Éthiopie et quelques paroles en amharique à la fin)
Il chante, nous sommes tous les descendants d'Adam et Eve. Nous devons donc nous aimer en tant que frères et sœurs. Nous sommes de la terre, nous retournons a la terre. Le salut ne peut pas venir de la prétention «Je suis de cette race ou je suis de cette ethnie». Notre acte sur la terre est notre garantie de salut. Nous devons éviter le tribalisme et le racisme et nous aimer les uns les autres, peu importe d'où nous venons.
Dishtagina est la nouvelle année du peuple Ari. Il dit que le passé soit révolu et reçois la nouvelle année avec un nouvel espoir et un nouvel amour!

original:
Dear Non Ethiopian Listeners,
I am amazed by your deep interest in Ethiopian music and for that I applaud you. In my opinion, the song went viral because of the message and the openness of TARIKU about his personal life on live TV interview. Tariku was born and grown up in the rural part of southern Ethiopia. He served in the military and fought a war in the North. Life was challenging for him when he was in the capital Addis Ababa. He worked as a day laborer and was living homeless life in the streets. Lastly, he decided to go back to his place of birth to break from the hustle and bustle of Addis Ababa . But the challenge he faced was that his people disowned him because of his gangster look with the long dread hair. He then went to local church and prayed to GOD to reveal his talent and make him somebody. Now he lives in the jungle as a farmer. He is the father of 5 kids. The meaning of his father's name [Gankisi] is "To break bad habits." He is happy with his life and never complains. He is full of positive energy and exerts this magnetic power in to the crowd with laughter.

DISHTA GHINE means New Year in "ARI" language. It is an Afro -Asiatic > Omotic>South language.
He begins the song by calling all the months and asking everybody to forgive their wrong doings and hope the New Year to brings happiness. And then he says the following verses in Amharic and translated as follows:

Me and Adam( my father)
You and Eve (my bone)--he points his index finger towards his ribs[ reference to the Bible].
I came naked to this world and leave with nothing.
There is no best Ethnic group/race amongst ourselves.. 
Where does this Evil came from, we are all one.
Look up the sky, no one washes it or cleans it but it is amazingly beautiful.
It is here on Earth that "We do not have LOVE".
GOD judges you for what you did on earth.
You do not get salvation before God  based on your Ethnicity/race.
You came from there, I came from there, We all came from there, We are all one(This is where he grasps his chest)
We are scattered all over the world after the fall of Babylon from God's grace.
To this day, we do not have a true love. no matter how we sing about it.
What should we do ?
GOD judges you for what you did on earth.
You do not get salvation before God  based on your Ethnicity/race./2/

It is a dazzling, mesmerizing, inspirational, and spiritual song full of positivity that reminds everybody that "We are created in the image of GOD.

Solomon Tadesse
Boston, Massachusetts

@brahimbelhaj3538  
Unfortunately, I don't have any video of it for the moment. I just started being interested about the Berber people because here in Europe where I live, the moroccans keep telling me all time that I look like the Berber people. And, I started my investigation in Ethiopia and the only information I've for the moment is that, effectively they immigrated from Agew. Ethiopia is a country of more than 80 different ethnic groups, each of them with their own language and culture. But what I've noticed is that, the culture of the Berber people has special similarity with the people of the northern part of Ethiopia. One of the reasons why I want to visit Morocco is to know more about them in first hand.

text: Amazigh people are native Africans They originated around Ancient Egypt and Lybia As a cyclical cultural continuity many people in the Sahara region have ancient Historical contacts Even with this diverse sparse land People have traded traveled and influenced one an other since antiquity In ancient time transSaharan traders used to navigate from the tip of Somaliland up to the riff atlas mountain Many Western Historians now a days like to to ignore this fact There was a trade route named Neqada Behir which traders from Mediterranean Red sea and Atlantic ocean used to meet Still the significant impact and the clear trace they made is undeniable Ps It is better if you dont use the name Berber to refer your self The more acceptable term should be Amazigh Imazighen or any of your tribe name The term BerberBarabarian is derogatory word given to them by Europeans
original:
Amazigh people are native Africans. They originated around Ancient Egypt and Lybia. As a cyclical cultural continuity, many people in the Sahara region have ancient Historical contacts. Even with this diverse sparse land. People have traded / traveled and influenced one an other since antiquity. In ancient time trans-Saharan traders used to navigate from the tip of Somali-land up to the riff atlas mountain. Many Western Historians now a days like to to ignore this fact, There was a trade route named " Neqada Behir ", which traders from Mediterranean, Red sea and Atlantic ocean used to meet. Still the significant impact and the clear trace they made is un-deniable.

P.s. It is better if you don't use the name "Berber" to refer your self. The more acceptable term should be Amazigh / Imazighen or any of your tribe name. The term Berber/Barabarian is derogatory word given to them by Europeans.

GOD judges you for what you did on earth.

"I brought nothing down and I don't take anything back up. Who called the pure seed a chaff? Adam my brother, me and Adam my one father. You and Eve my one bone. Woe earth woe. I'm from you, you're from me, but love is lost. You are from there (above), I am from there. @cubadebesai1356  I got this from another comment of a guy named Solomon the lyrics are at the bottom the song is using 2 languages and the amharic language part of the song is below for you, -------Tariku the singer was born and grown up in the rural part of southern Ethiopia. He served in the military and fought a war in the North. Life was challenging for him when he was in the capital Addis Ababa. He worked as a day laborer and was living homeless life in the streets. Lastly, he decided to go back to his place of birth to break from the hustle and bustle of Addis Ababa . But the challenge he faced was that his people disowned him because of his gangster look with the long dread hair. He then went to local church and prayed to GOD to reveal his talent and make him somebody. Now he lives in the jungle as a farmer. He is the father of 5 kids. The meaning of his father's name [Gankisi] is "To break bad habits." He is happy with his life and never complains. He is full of positive energy and exerts this magnetic power in to the crowd with laughter.

DISHTA GHINE means New Year in "ARI" language. It is an Afro -Asiatic > Omotic>South language.
He begins the song by calling all the months and asking everybody to forgive their wrong doings and hope the New Year to brings happiness. And then he says the following verses in Amharic and translated as follows:

Me and Adam( my father)
You and Eve (my bone)--he points his index finger towards his ribs[ reference to the Bible].
I came naked to this world and leave with nothing.
There is no best Ethnic group/race amongst ourselves.. 
Where does this Evil came from, we are all one.
Look up the sky, no one washes it or cleans it but it is amazingly beautiful.
It is here on Earth that "We do not have LOVE".
GOD judges you for what you did on earth.
You do not get salvation before God  based on your Ethnicity/race.
You came from there, I came from there, We all came from there, We are all one(This is where he grasps his chest)
We are scattered all over the world after the fall of Babylon from God's grace.
To this day, we do not have a true love. no matter how we sing about it.
What should we do ?
GOD judges you for what you did on earth.

You do not get salvation before God  based on your Ethnicity/race./2/

I don't know what he says in the Ari language, but in Amharic he says:
"I brought nothing down and I don't take anything back up. Who called the pure seed a chaff? Adam my brother, me and Adam my one father. You and Eve my one bone. Woe earth woe. I'm from you, you're from me, but love is lost. You are from there (above), I am from there. text: I dont know what he says in the Ari language but in Amharic he says I brought nothing down and I dont take anything back up Who decided the pure seed and the chaff Adam my brother me and Adam my one father You and Eve my one bone Its what we do on earth we have to answer for When we stand before Him seed race doesnt make you righteous No one washes her no one sweeps her but look at the sky how beautiful she is Woe earth woe Im from you youre from me but love is lost You are from there above I am from there Babylon dispersed us and until this day we lost true love nothing to sing nothing to chant Whats better for us now The song fades out as he repeats it At 0117 Dishta Gina Dishta Gina Gail babo Dishta Gina Barged babo a Dishta Gina Sida babo irar Dishta Gina Seiti babo irar Dishta Gina Teyye babo irar Dishta Gina Baka babo irar Dishta Gina Huba babo hura Dishta Gine Laide babo hura Dishta Gine Woze babo hibaa goyse akka Arit Dishta Gine Arit Dishta Gine My favorite section
original:
I don't know what he says in the Ari language, but in Amharic he says:
"I brought nothing down and I don't take anything back up. Who decided the pure seed and the chaff? Adam my brother, me and Adam my one father. You and Eve my one bone. It's what we do on earth we have to answer for. When we stand before Him, seed (race) doesn't make you righteous. No one washes her, no one sweeps her, but look at the sky how beautiful she is. Woe earth woe. I'm from you, you're from me, but love is lost. You are from there (above), I am from there. Babylon dispersed us, and until this day we lost true love; nothing to sing, nothing to chant. What's better for us now?" The song fades out as he repeats it.

text: I am from Eritrea ግጥሙ ባይገባኝ ዝም ብላህ ብታዳምጦ ግጥሙ ላይ የሆነ ልቢ የሚንካ ንገር ኖው። ክሊቡ ላይ ያሉ ልጆች ደስ ሲሉ ዶሞ። እግዛቢሄር ሰላሙ ያብዛለን ። እኔና አዳም አንድ አባቴ፣ አንቺና ሄዋን አንድ አጥንቴ፣ ታድያ ይዤ የመጣሁት ይዤ ምመለሰዉ አንድም ነገር የለም፣ ታድያ ምርጡ ዘር እንክርዳድ ማነው ያለው ምነው የምድር ስራ እንጂ ሚያስጠይቅ በርሱ ፊት ስንቆም ዘር አያፀድቅ። አይይይ ሚያጥባት የለ ሚጠርጋት የለ ሰማይን እያት አቤት ማማሯ፣ አይይይይ ወይኔ ምድር ወይኔ እኔ ካንቺ አንቺ ከኔ፣ ፍቅር ጠፋ ፍቅር ጠፋ ዘምበል ብለህ እያ፣ አንዱ አባቴ አዳም ወንድሜ እኔና አዳም አንድ አባቴ እኔና ሄዋን አንድ አጥንቴ እኔ ከዛ መጣሁ አንቺም ከዛ መጣሽ አንተ ከዛ መጣህ መሃል ምን ገባ እይይይ

original:
Dear Non Ethiopian Listeners,
I am amazed by your deep interest in Ethiopian music and for that I applaud you. In my opinion, the song went viral because of the message and the openness of TARIKU about his personal life on live TV interview. Tariku was born and grown up in the rural part of southern Ethiopia. He served in the military and fought a war in the North. Life was challenging for him when he was in the capital Addis Ababa. He worked as a day laborer and was living homeless life in the streets. Lastly, he decided to go back to his place of birth to break from the hustle and bustle of Addis Ababa . But the challenge he faced was that his people disowned him because of his gangster look with the long dread hair. He then went to local church and prayed to GOD to reveal his talent and make him somebody. Now he lives in the jungle as a farmer. He is the father of 5 kids. The meaning of his father's name [Gankisi] is "To break bad habits." He is happy with his life and never complains. He is full of positive energy and exerts this magnetic power in to the crowd with laughter.

DISHTA GHINE means New Year in "ARI" language. It is an Afro -Asiatic > Omotic>South language.
He begins the song by calling all the months and asking everybody to forgive their wrong doings and hope the New Year to brings happiness. And then he says the following verses in Amharic and translated as follows:

Me and Adam( my father)
You and Eve (my bone)--he points his index finger towards his ribs[ reference to the Bible].
I came naked to this world and leave with nothing.
There is no best Ethnic group/race amongst ourselves.. 
Where does this Evil came from, we are all one.
Look up the sky, no one washes it or cleans it but it is amazingly beautiful.
It is here on Earth that "We do not have LOVE".
GOD judges you for what you did on earth.
You do not get salvation before God  based on your Ethnicity/race.
You came from there, I came from there, We all came from there, We are all one(This is where he grasps his chest)
We are scattered all over the world after the fall of Babylon from God's grace.
To this day, we do not have a true love. no matter how we sing about it.
What should we do ?
GOD judges you for what you did on earth.

You do not get salvation before God  based on your Ethnicity/race./2/

It is a dazzling, mesmerizing, inspirational, and spiritual song full of positivity that reminds everybody that "We are created in the image of GOD.

Solomon Tadesse
Boston, Massachusetts

text: Most Ethiopians are ignorant of the language of the lyrics of this song because it is a language specific to a simple southern region but the idea of the song and its lyrics are about brotherhood between all Ethiopian races and the rejection of division and discrimination between the people of the same nation This song was met with unprecedented admiration and acceptance among all Ethiopians This singer was honored rewarded celebrated and encouraged by the countrys Prime Minister personally and many Ethiopian businessmen and social figures This song contributed greatly to reminding Ethiopians of all the common denominators between them and the proof of its success is its popularity and acceptance by all Ethiopians

This singer was honored, rewarded, celebrated and encouraged by the country's Prime Minister personally and many Ethiopian businessmen and social figures. This song contributed greatly to reminding Ethiopians of all the common denominators between them, and the proof of its success is its popularity and acceptance by all Ethiopians.

text: This is the translation of the song Me and Adam are one bonerace You and Eve are one bone of mine I brought nothing to this world and I will not take anything when I leave this world too So who said one is pure breed and the other a weed We will be judged by our deeds on this earth and our race will not make us righteous when we stand in front of Him God Look at the sky oh how beautiful it is No one clears it and no one washes it Oh earth oh earth there is no love between us Look down on us my one father and brother Adam You came from there and I came from there too but what entered among us
original:
This is the translation of the song :

Me and Adam are one bone/race. 

You and Eve are one bone of mine. 

I brought nothing to this world, and I will not take anything when I leave this world too. 

So, who said one is pure breed and the other a weed? 

We will be judged by our deeds on this earth, and our race will not make us righteous when we stand in front of Him (God). 

Look at the sky, oh how beautiful it is! No one clears it, and no one washes it. 

Oh earth, oh earth, there is no love between us. 

Look down on us, my one father and brother, Adam. 

You came from there, and I came from there too, but what entered among us?

text: ihatepolitica9600 ጀግናው የትግራይ ወጣት እማ ህዝቡም ሀገሩም ለማስከበር መስዋት እየከፈለ ነው ጫካ ገብቶ ያልሹው ደሞ የኢትዮጵያ መከላክያ ፣ አማራ ምልሻ ፣ የኤርትራም መከላክያ አልበቃ ብሎ መንግስት እርዳታ እየፈለገልሽ ነው ትግራይ ላይ ምን ያክል ጀግና መከላክያ እንዳለ በዚህ መገመት አይከብድም የኢትዮጵያ ሆነ ኤርትራ ጫካ ገብቶ ከመዋጋት ይልቅ ቤት ለቤት ንፁሃንን መግደል፣መድፈር፣መስረቅ ሆነ ስራቸው so ማንም ሽንታም ትግራይ ሆነ ተጋሩ መግደል መድፈር መብት የለው የ ግዜ ጉዳይ እንጂ አሁንም ቅዘናም
